   <p>The Iron Act of 1750 prohibited the use of tilt hammers in American ironworks, and the Woollen Act of 1699 prohibited the American export of wool cloth either overseas or in intercolonial trade (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Lawrence Henry Gipson, &lt;i&gt;The British Empire before the American Revolution&lt;/i&gt;, Caldwell, Idaho, and New York, 19361970; 15 vols. ]">Gipson, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Empire before the Revolution</span></span>, 1:219220; 3:227). But see <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr>s 1775 comment in the fourth number of Novanglus that the prohibition of tilt hammers was never executed, vol. <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-02-02-0072-0005#ADMS-06-02-02-pb-0261" class="pageNo">2:261</a>.</p>
</div>
          
